  Test results


  ============================================================
  Update — Admin Product Management Fix (later same day)
  ============================================================

  Reported issue
    /admin/urunler/25 showed the public "404 Sayfa Bulunamadı" page (with public Navbar/Footer)
    instead of opening an admin edit screen. Admin could not add or edit products from the UI.

  Root cause
    apps/web/src/app/admin/urunler/AdminProductsClient.tsx linked to /admin/urunler/[id] and
    /admin/urunler/yeni, but neither route file existed. Next.js fell through to the global
    app/not-found.tsx which is rendered with the public root layout (Navbar + Footer).

  Files created
    - apps/web/src/app/admin/urunler/yeni/page.tsx               → "Yeni Ürün" page
    - apps/web/src/app/admin/urunler/[id]/page.tsx               → edit route, validates numeric id
    - apps/web/src/app/admin/urunler/[id]/EditProductClient.tsx  → fetches product, handles
                                                                   404/401/403 inside admin shell
    - apps/web/src/app/admin/urunler/ProductForm.tsx             → shared create/edit form,
                                                                   client-side validation mirrors
                                                                   server Zod schema, slug
                                                                   auto-generation, dynamic image
                                                                   rows, loading/success/error
    - apps/web/src/app/admin/urunler/form.module.css             → responsive form styles
                                                                   (2-col → 1-col ≤640px)
    - apps/web/src/app/admin/not-found.tsx                       → admin-scoped 404 keeps the
                                                                   admin layout for unknown
                                                                   /admin/* URLs

  Files modified
    - CLAUDE.md  → appended "Review Notes — 2026-05-07" section with routes, commands, manual
                   test checklist, responsiveness notes, and remaining recommendations.

  Admin product features now working from the UI
    - List products (existing).
    - Create product (title, slug auto + override, description, price Decimal, stock, category,
      isActive, multiple image URL/alt rows).
    - Edit product (prefilled via GET /api/admin/products/:id, PATCH on save; image set
      replaced atomically in a Prisma transaction — already supported server-side).
    - Soft delete via existing DELETE /api/admin/products/:id (sets isActive=false).
    - Graceful in-admin error for unknown ids (e.g. /admin/urunler/9999) — no public 404.

  Security verification (no regressions)
    - apps/web/src/app/admin/layout.tsx still server-side checks /api/auth/me with forwarded
      cookies → redirects non-authenticated to /giris and non-ADMIN to /. Applies to every
      /admin/* page, including the new ones.
    - apps/api/src/app.ts mounts every admin router behind requireAdmin middleware
      (apps/api/src/middleware/auth.ts) → server-side enforcement on every admin API call.
      UI hiding is not relied on.

  Database
    - No schema changes needed. Existing Product/ProductImage/Category models cover all fields.

  Routes reference (admin, ADMIN role only)
    /admin, /admin/urunler, /admin/urunler/yeni, /admin/urunler/[id],
    /admin/siparisler, /admin/yorumlar.

  Manual test checklist
    1. Login as admin@guzellikmerkezi.com.tr / Admin1234! at /giris.
    2. /admin/urunler lists 25 seeded products.
    3. + Yeni Ürün → submit valid form → redirects to /admin/urunler/<newId>.
    4. Düzenle → change price/category → save → "Ürün güncellendi.".
    5. Visit /admin/urunler/25 directly → loads existing product (no 404).
    6. Visit /admin/urunler/9999 → in-admin error card, not public 404.
    7. Logout → /admin/* → redirected to /giris.
    8. Non-admin user → /admin/* → redirected to /.

  Responsiveness
    - Admin sidebar already collapses ≤768px.
    - New form grid 2-col → 1-col ≤640px; image rows 3-col → 1-col ≤640px.
    - Action buttons wrap on narrow viewports.

  Remaining recommendations (out of scope)
    - Hide public Navbar/Footer on /admin/* for cleaner admin chrome.
    - Add image upload pipeline (Cloudinary already allow-listed in next.config.mjs).
    - Add Playwright e2e covering admin create/edit/delete.


  ============================================================
  Update — Admin Image Upload from Computer (later same day)
  ============================================================

  Feature
    Admin can now upload product images directly from their computer (no manual URL needed).
    Files are stored on the API server's disk and are physically deleted when the admin removes
    them from a product or replaces them on save.

  How it works
    - New API route: POST /api/admin/uploads (multipart "file") → stores under
      apps/api/uploads/products/<timestamp>-<uuid>.<ext>, returns { url, filename }.
      url is a relative path "/uploads/products/<filename>".
    - New API route: DELETE /api/admin/uploads/:filename → removes the file from disk.
      Path traversal is blocked (basename + regex check + resolved-path containment check).
    - Both routes are mounted behind requireAdmin middleware in apps/api/src/app.ts.
    - apps/api/src/app.ts also serves the uploads folder publicly read-only at /uploads
      (express.static with maxAge: 7d). Writes are admin-only via the upload route.
    - apps/web/next.config.mjs gains a /uploads/:path* rewrite to the API so images load
      same-origin from the web app (no CORS, no remotePatterns hassle).
    - apps/api/src/routes/admin/products.ts image-URL validator now accepts either an
      absolute http(s) URL or a relative "/uploads/..." path (max 500 chars).

  Validation & limits
    - Max file size: 5 MB (multer).
    - Allowed mime types: image/jpeg, image/png, image/webp, image/avif, image/gif.
    - Filenames are server-generated (timestamp + UUID); original names never reach disk.

  UI changes (apps/web/src/app/admin/urunler/ProductForm.tsx + form.module.css)
    - Each image row now has: thumbnail preview, URL input, alt input, "Yükle" button
      (file picker), and "Sil" button.
    - Yükle uploads instantly and writes the resulting "/uploads/..." URL into the row.
    - Replacing an image (re-uploading into a row that already has an unsaved upload)
      cleans up the previous file server-side automatically.
    - Sil deletes the physical file when the URL is one of our uploads (with confirm prompt).
    - On save (edit mode), any *originally-saved* upload URL that was removed from the form
      is best-effort deleted from disk so we don't leak files (matches the API's
      replace-all image strategy).
    - Responsive: 84px preview + inputs + actions on desktop; collapses to single column
      with a 160px-tall preview ≤640px.

  Files created
    - apps/api/src/routes/admin/uploads.ts

  Files modified
    - apps/api/package.json                              → +multer, +@types/multer
    - apps/api/src/app.ts                                → static /uploads + new admin route
    - apps/api/src/routes/admin/products.ts              → image URL validator relaxed
    - apps/web/next.config.mjs                           → /uploads rewrite
    - apps/web/src/app/admin/urunler/ProductForm.tsx     → file upload + delete-on-remove
    - apps/web/src/app/admin/urunler/form.module.css     → image row layout w/ preview
    - .gitignore                                         → ignore apps/api/uploads/

  Setup step required after pulling
    Run: pnpm install   (installs multer + @types/multer)
    Then: pnpm --filter @niltellioglu/api dev
          pnpm --filter @niltellioglu/web dev

  Manual test
    1. Login as admin, open /admin/urunler/yeni.
    2. + Görsel Ekle → click "Yükle" → choose a JPG/PNG → preview appears, URL field
       fills with "/uploads/products/...".
    3. Save the product → image is reachable at /urunler/<slug> on the public site.
    4. Re-open in admin, click "Sil" on the image row → file is removed from
       apps/api/uploads/products/ on disk.
    5. Try uploading a 6 MB file → blocked with "Dosya 5 MB'dan büyük olamaz.".
    6. Try uploading a .pdf → blocked with "Desteklenmeyen dosya türü.".
    7. As non-admin, POST /api/admin/uploads → 403.

  Security notes
    - DELETE filename is validated as a basename matching [A-Za-z0-9._-]+ and is
      additionally checked to resolve inside the products dir → no path traversal.
    - Static /uploads is read-only; only the admin route can write/delete.
    - File extension is chosen from the validated mime, not from the user-supplied filename.


  ============================================================
  Update — Product Gallery, Upload Security, and Frontend QA
  ============================================================

  Context
    Follow-up work after admin product editing exposed two practical issues:
    1. Public product detail pages received multiple images from the API but only displayed
       the first image as the main product image.
    2. Admin uploads accepted files based on client-provided multipart MIME type only.

  Public product gallery
    - Product detail pages now support multiple product photos with an interactive gallery.
    - Users can switch photos by clicking thumbnails or by using previous/next controls.
    - The gallery displays an image counter such as "1 / 2" and highlights the active
      thumbnail.
    - The product detail route already returned all images from
      GET /api/products/:slug; no API change was needed for the public detail page.
    - Product listing pages still intentionally request and render only the first image as
      the card thumbnail.

  Files created
    - apps/web/src/app/urunler/[slug]/ProductGallery.tsx

  Files modified
    - apps/web/src/app/urunler/[slug]/page.tsx
        Replaced the static first-image markup with ProductGallery.
    - apps/web/src/app/urunler/[slug]/page.module.css
        Added gallery layout, active thumbnail styling, horizontal thumbnail scroll,
        arrow controls, and image counter styling.
    - apps/web/src/app/urunler/page.tsx
        Added priority={index === 0} to the first product card image to satisfy the
        Next.js LCP warning found during frontend QA.

  Admin upload security hardening
    Finding:
      POST /api/admin/uploads trusted the multipart Content-Type/MIME metadata. A non-image
      payload could be uploaded into the publicly served /uploads/products directory by
      labeling it as image/png.

    Fix:
      - apps/api/src/routes/admin/uploads.ts now validates the actual file signature after
        multer writes the file.
      - Supported signatures: JPEG, PNG, WEBP, AVIF, GIF.
      - If the signature does not match the declared allowed MIME type, the uploaded file is
        immediately deleted and the API returns 415 with "Dosya geçerli bir görsel değil."
      - Existing filename generation, file size limit, path traversal protection, and
        requireAdmin mounting remain in place.

  Security tests added
    - apps/api/src/tests/uploads.security.test.ts
        1. Rejects fake "<script>" bytes submitted as image/png.
        2. Accepts a minimal valid PNG upload and removes the uploaded test file.

  Security validation
    - Pre-fix reproducer:
        pnpm --filter @niltellioglu/api exec vitest run src/tests/uploads.security.test.ts
        Result before fix: failed because fake image/png returned 201.
    - Post-fix focused test:
        pnpm --filter @niltellioglu/api exec vitest run src/tests/uploads.security.test.ts
        Result: 2 passed.
    - Full API test suite:
        pnpm --filter @niltellioglu/api run test
        Result: 22 passed.
    - API typecheck:
        pnpm --filter @niltellioglu/api run typecheck
        Result: passed.
    - API lint:
        pnpm --filter @niltellioglu/api run lint
        Result: could not run because eslint is not installed/available in the API workspace.

  Frontend QA
    Browser plugin was not available in the Codex session, so regular Playwright was used.

    Existing repo e2e:
      pnpm test:e2e
      Result: 8 passed.

    Additional temporary QA harness:
      - Temporary script: C:\tmp\frontend-qa-niltellioglu.mjs
      - Screenshots: C:\tmp\niltellioglu-frontend-qa\
      - These are intentionally outside the repo and are not source artifacts.

    Covered flows:
      - Desktop home page renders and has correct title.
      - Mobile nav menu opens and shows scoped navigation links.
      - Product listing renders product cards.
      - Product detail renders and gallery next control changes "1 / 2" to "2 / 2".
      - Add-to-cart while logged out redirects to /giris.
      - Wrong login credentials show the Turkish auth error.
      - Register page form renders.
      - Unauthenticated cart shows empty-cart state after hydration.
      - Contact form submits and shows "Mesajınız başarıyla gönderildi!".
      - Admin login with seeded admin reaches /admin.
      - Admin product list and new-product form render.
      - Relevant console errors/warnings: clean after the LCP priority fix.

  Local dev environment notes
    - Port conflicts:
        Next.js uses 3000 and API uses 4000. If EADDRINUSE appears, stop the process
        currently listening on that port before restarting pnpm dev.
    - argon2 on Windows:
        If the API fails with missing argon2.node, rebuild the native dependency from the
        API workspace:
          pnpm --filter @niltellioglu/api rebuild argon2
        Validation:
          pnpm --filter @niltellioglu/api exec node -e "require('argon2'); console.log('argon2 ok')"

  Current known limitations / follow-up
    - Payment flow was not fully tested in browser QA.
    - Admin product creation form was rendered but not submitted during QA to avoid creating
      extra test products in the live local database.
    - Browser QA covered Chromium only, not Firefox/Safari.
    - The seeded product "oud-unisex-parfum" currently has two images and was used to verify
      the gallery switching behavior.




